===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|sheep}}, {{m|enm|scheep}}, {{m|enm|schep}}, {{m|enm|schepe}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|scēap}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*skēpą}} (compare {{etyl|fy|-}} {{m|fy|skiep}}, {{etyl|frr|-}} {{m|frr|schäip}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{m|nl|schaap}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{m|de|Schaf}}), beside {{m|gem-pro|*keppô}} (compare {{etyl|non|-}} {{m|non|kjappi||he-goat}}, dialectal {{etyl|de|-}} {{m|de|Kippe||newborn calf}}), of unknown origin. Perhaps from the same {{etyl|xsc|en}} word (compare {{etyl|os|-}} {{m|os|цӕу||goat}}, {{etyl|fa|-}} {{m|fa|چپش||yearling goat|tr=čapiš}})<ref>Vladimir Orel, ''A Handbook of Germanic Etymology'', s.vv. "*keppōn", "*skēpan" (Leiden: Brill, 2003), 213, 340</ref> which was borrowed into {{etyl|sq|-}} as {{m|sq|cjap}}, {{m|sq|sqap||he-goat}} and into Slavic (compare {{etyl|pl|-}} {{m|pl|cap}}).  After Kroonen, ''*skēpą'' is instead from the root of Proto-Germanic {{m|gem-pro|*skabaną||to scratch}} via [[w:Kluge's law|Kluge's law]].<ref>Guus Kroonen (2011), ''The Proto-Germanic ''n-''stems: a study in diachronic morphophonology'' [http://books.google.de/books?id=9stMq8rRnCMC], Rodopi, ISBN 9042032936.</ref>

